04189nam a22005055i 9780773561861DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19891989xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735618617 a10.1515/97807735618612doi  a(DE-B1597)655128  a(OCoLC)732600654  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDA957bK46 1989eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a941.081 aKendle, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIreland and the Federal Solution :bThe Debate over the United Kingdom Constitution, 1870-1920 /cJohn Kendle. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1989] 4c©1989  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tEarly Schemes and Ideas, 1840-1885 -- tGladstonian Home Rule -- tHome Rule All Round, 1886-1899 -- tDevolution, 1900-1909 -- tConstitutional Crisis, 1910 -- tHome Rule or “Federalism”? -- tUlster and the Federal Solution, 1912-1914 -- tThe War Years -- tFederal Devolution, 1919-1921 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tA Note on Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe debate over internal constitutional change took place at a time when many people were concerned about relations between Great Britain and the self-governing colonies. The issue of Imperial federation was continuously and exhaustively discussed and promoted from the late 1860s through World War I. The waters became so muddied that at times it has been difficult to separate arguments for closer imperial union from proposals for internal decentralization. Kendle comments extensively on this confusion. During the fifty years from the early 1870s to the establishment of the Irish Free State in 1922, politicians and publicists devoted considerable energy and attention to the notions of "home rule all round," "devolution," and "federalism" as possible means of resolving the urgent political, administrative, and constitutional issues confronting the United Kingdom. The increasing complexity of government business, the gathering forces of ethnic nationalism in Ireland, Scotland, and Wales, and concern with maintaining and strengthening the role of the parliament at Westminister in imperial affairs combined to keep the possibility of decentralization at the forefront of political and public debate. Kendle explores and analyzes the motives and attitudes of participants in this debate and looks at the schemes and proposals that resulted from this power struggle. Ireland and the Federal Solution gives a lucid appraisal of what was meant at the time by the terms "federalism," "home rule all round," and "devolution" and evaluates how firmly the participants grasped the constitutional similarities and differences between existing federal systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356186140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773561861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773561861/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles